The '''purple-rumped sunbird''' ('''''Leptocoma zeylonica''''') is a [[sunbird]] endemic to the Indian Subcontinent. Like other sunbirds, they are small in size, feeding mainly on [[nectar]] but sometimes take insects, particularly when feeding young. They can hover for short durations but usually perch to lap nectar from flowers. They build a hanging pouch nest made up of cobwebs, [[lichen]]s and plant material. Males are contrastingly coloured but females are olive above and yellow to buff below. Males are easily distinguished from the [[purple sunbird]] by the light coloured underside while females can be told apart from males by their whitish throats.

==Description==

Purple-rumped sunbirds are tiny, at less than {{ Convert | 10 | cm | 0 }} long. They have medium-length thin down-curved bills and brush-tipped tubular tongues, both adaptations for nectar feeding. Purple-rumped sunbirds are [[sexual dimorphism|sexually dimorphic]]. The males have a dark maroon upperside with a blue-green crown that glistens at some angles, bright green shoulder patch and violet/purple rump patch which is generally hidden under the wings. The underparts are whitish with dark throat, maroon breast band and purple/violet patch in the throat which is visible in some angles. The iris is generally reddish in color. In the [[Western Ghats]], it can overlap in some areas with the [[crimson-backed sunbird]] but the male of that species has reddish upperparts, a broader breast band and generally darker eyes. The female has a white throat followed by yellowish breast. The upperside is olive or brownish. The uppertail coverts are black and a weak supercilium may be visible. The nominate subspecies from Sri Lanka has a more bluish violet throat whereas the Indian form ''flaviventris'' (two other proposed populations ''whistleri'' from Maddur in Karnataka and  ''sola'' from Pondicherry are subsumed) has a more pinkish tinge.<ref name=pcr>{{cite book|author1=Rasmussen PC  |author2=JC Anderton |name-list-style=amp |year=2005|title=Birds of South Asia: The Ripley Guide. |publisher=Smithsonian Institution & Lynx Edicions.|volume=2|page=547}}</ref>

Their call is ''ptsiee ptsit, ptsiee ptsswit'' or a sharp twittering ''tityou, titou, trrrtit, tityou...''.<ref name=hbk>{{cite book|pages=23–25|author1=Ali, Salim|author2=Ripley, Sidney Dillon|name-list-style=amp |year=1999|title=Handbook of the birds of India and Pakistan|edition=2nd|volume=10|publisher=Oxford University Press}}</ref>

==Distribution==
The purple-rumped sunbird is a common resident breeder in southern [[India]], [[Sri Lanka]] and [[Bangladesh]]. It is found in Gujarat to the west<ref>{{cite journal|author=Khacher, Lavkumar |year=2000 |title= Range extension of the Purplerumped Sunbird ''Nectarinia zeylonica''. |journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume= 97|issue=1|page=146|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48567572}}</ref> (possibly a recent expansion<ref>{{cite journal|author=Khacher, Lavkumar |year=2000|title= Purplerumped Sunbird ''Nectarinia zeylonica'' (Linn.) at Gandhinagar, Gujarat. |journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume= 97|issue=3|pages=431–432|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48567875}}</ref>) and extending into Assam (Hailakandi<ref>{{cite journal|author=Choudhury, Anwaruddin |author-link=Anwaruddin Choudhury |year=1991 |title= Purplerumped Sunbird ''Nectarinia zeylonica'' (Linn.): a new record for Assam. |journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.  |volume=88|issue=1|page=114|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48673520}}</ref>) or Meghalaya<ref name=pcr/> in the east. Records from [[Myanmar]] are not certain.<ref name=pcr/> This species is found in a variety of habitats with trees, including scrub and cultivation and is usually absent from dense forest.

==Behaviour and ecology==

They breed through the year and may have two broods,<ref>{{cite book|author=Whistler, Hugh|year=1949|title=Popular handbook of Indian birds|publisher=Gurney & Jackson, London|url=https://archive.org/details/popularhandbooko033226mbp| pages= [https://archive.org/details/popularhandbooko033226mbp/page/n317 270]–271}}</ref> but mainly during the monsoons.<ref name="pcr" /> The nest is made up of fine plant fibres, cobwebs and is studded on the exterior with lichens, bark pieces, flying seeds and other materials. The nest is constructed by the female alone although the male may fly alongside her. The nest is lined with soft fibres such as from the fuzz covering the seeds of ''[[Calotropis]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hume, A.O.|volume=2|edition=2nd|year=1890|publisher=R H Porter London|url=https://www.archive.org/details/nestseggsofindia02humerich|pages=263–267|title=The nests and eggs of Indian Birds}}</ref> The nest is placed on the end of branch and the entrance usually faces a bush.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Bharucha, Erach K |year=1983 |title= Nest-building error by a female Purplerumped Sunbird. |journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.  |volume=80|issue=1|page= 220|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48743810}}</ref> Nests may sometimes be built close to buildings or under open porches.<ref>{{cite journal|author=George, N.J. |year=1982 |title= Purplerumped Sunbird ''Nectarinia zeylonica'' nesting on the loosely fixed wiring under the concrete sunshade of the house. |journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] |volume=22|issue=11–12|page= 11}}</ref> The female stays in the nest at night a couple of day before laying the eggs. The clutch consists of two eggs which are generally oval, pale greenish and white with spots and streaks, becoming more dense at the broad end. Sometimes, eggs may be plain grey without markings as well.<ref>{{cite journal|author=H. Daniel Wesley|year=2004|title= A glimpse of the breeding biology of the Purple-rumped Sunbird Nectarinia zeylonica (Linnaeus, 1766) |journal=[[Newsletter for Ornithologists]] |volume=1|issue=1–2|pages= 9–10}}</ref> When collecting cobwebs they are often seen at windows of homes, a time when they also sometimes end up tapping the window, possibly at their own reflection.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Green, E. E. |year=1907|title=Window-tapping by birds|journal=Spolia Zeylanica |volume=5|issue=17|pages=65–66|url=https://archive.org/stream/spoliazeylanica05nati#page/64/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Ryan, James |year=1908|title= The Purple-rumped Sunbird|journal=Spolia Zeylanica |volume=5|issue=18|pages=110–111|url=https://archive.org/stream/spoliazeylanica05nati#page/110/mode/2up}}</ref> The eggs are usually laid in the morning. The eggs are incubated by both the male and female. The incubation period varies from 14 to 16 days. The chicks fledge in about 17 days and continue to be fed by the male for a few days. [[Helpers at the nest|Helpers]], females or possibly juveniles from the previous brood may sometimes assist the parents in feeding the young.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Ganguly, Jayanta Kumar |year=1986|title= Co-operative feeding of chicks of the Purplerumped Sunbird (''Nectarinia zeylonica'')|journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.  |volume=83 |issue=2 |page=447|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48761454}}</ref> Old nests are sometimes reused.<ref name="hbk" /> Cases of nests being parasitised by the [[grey-bellied cuckoo]] are known. In one case the cuckoo was fed by an adult sunbird as well as an adult [[common tailorbird]].<ref>{{cite journal| title=Sunbirds fostering fledglings of the plaintive cuckoos|author=Bharucha, Erach K|year=1981|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=79|pages=670–671|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48745118}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Suter, MF|year=1944|title=Plaintive Cuckoo (?) parasitising purple sunbird|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=45|issue=2|page=235|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48126933}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Wesley, H.D. |year=1996 |title= Breeding behaviour of ''Nectarinia zeylonica'' at two latitudes in the Indian peninsula |journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] |volume=36|issue=2|pages= 28–29|url=https://archive.org/stream/NLBW36_2#page/n9/mode/1up}}</ref>

They [[ornithophily|pollinate]] the flowers of many plant species such as ''[[Bruguiera]]'', ''[[Woodfordia]]'', ''[[Hamelia]]'' and ''[[Sterculia]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Raju, Aluri Jacob Solomon|title=Passerine bird pollination and seed dispersal in Woodfordia floribunda Salisb. (Lythraceae), a common low altitude woody shrub in the Eastern Ghats forests of India|journal=Ornithological Science|volume=4|pages=103–108 |year=2005|doi=10.2326/osj.4.103|issue=2|s2cid=198150132|doi-access=free}}</ref> They tend to perch while foraging for nectar and do not hover as much as the syntopic Loten's sunbird.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Reuben, Rachel|year=1984|title=Feeding behaviour of sunbirds, ''Nectarinia zeylonica'' and ''N. lotenia''|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.| volume=83|issue=2|pages=446–447|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48761453}}</ref> It has been noted that they maintain special scratching posts, where they get rid of pollen and nectar sticking to their head.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Nagarajan, B. |author2=M. Krishnamoorthy |author3=C. Pandiarajan |author4=A Manimekalan |year=2009|title=Can sweetness be difficult to handle when in excess?|journal=Current Science|issue=11|page=1433|url=http://www.ias.ac.in/currsci/jun102009/1433.pdf|volume=96}}</ref> When the flowers are too deep to probe, they sometimes pierce the base of the flower and rob the nectar, an action termed as "[[Nectar robbing|nectar theft]]" since the flower's primary purpose of attracting pollinators is foiled.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Nectar Robbing by the Purple-rumped Sunbird Nectarinia zeylonica from Introduced Flowers in Sri Lanka|author=Fujita K |journal=Japanese Journal of Ornithology|year=2000|volume=49|issue=4|pages=185–187|doi=10.3838/jjo.49.185|doi-access=free}}</ref> They sometimes visit open crop fields and take honeydew exuded by leafhoppers.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Sugary exudate of sorghum ''Sorghum bicolor'' as food of large grey babbler Turdoides malcolmi (Sykes), purplerumped sunbird ''Nectarinia zeylonica'' (Linn.) and redvented bulbul ''Pycnonotus cafer'' (Linnaeus)|author=Kumar, Satish|volume=92|issue=3|year=1995|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|pages=421–422|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48613982}}</ref>

Sunbird may indulge in dew-bathing, or bathing by sliding over drops of rain collected on large leaves.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Natarajan, V |author2=Balasubramanian, P |year=1992 |title= Dew bathing by Purplerumped Sunbird ''Nectarinia zeylonica'' (Linn.) |journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=89|issue=3|pages=377–378|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48732857}}</ref>

Like most birds they harbour specific protozoa species in their blood.  A species ''Haemoproteus raymundi'' has been described from a specimen from Goa but the identification and taxonomic placement of this malaria-like protozoan is disputed.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Avian Haemoproteidae. 19. The haemoproteids of the sunbirds (family Nectariniidae) and morphometric variation in Haemoproteus sequeirae|author=Bennett, Gordon F.|author2=Michael A. Peirce, Jennifer R. Caines |name-list-style=amp | journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology|year=1985|volume=63|issue=6|pages=1371–1376|doi=10.1139/z85-206}}</ref>

